	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName> <date>22d April 1861</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I should have<lb/> replied to your last favor earlier<lb/> but that I have had very little<lb/> leisure to do so.  With reference<lb/> to the <persName>Messrs Benjamins</persName> accounts<lb/> I have more than once called<lb/> their attention to their indebtedness<lb/> to you&#8212;as <persName>Mr Joseph</persName> has also<lb/> done.  I have no doubt <persName>Mr S. B.</persName><lb/> will settle before he leaves for<lb/> <placeName>Europe</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have taken no active<lb/> part in the commercial affairs<lb/> of our Calendar since I gave<lb/> you the former copies&#59; but I</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p><sic>I</sic> will send you a few copies<lb/> per earliest opportunity.  <persName>Mrs<lb/> Joseph</persName> goes soon I believe to<lb/> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have commenced<lb/> a Biography of my late reverd<lb/> father <add>Hebrew</add>&#59; but do not think<lb/> I shall publish it just yet&#8212;<lb/> I would gladly send it to the<lb/> Occident in its monthly form<lb/> but I was asked some time<lb/> back for a Biographical notice<lb/> by another Jewish paper and<lb/> <hi rend="underline">partially</hi> promised to give it<lb/> him.  In any case I should be<lb/> glad to see it in your columns<lb/> if you deemed it suitable.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I only live longer from<lb/> the unhappy hour of my beloved</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>parents death to realize more<lb/> and more the extent of his loss.<lb/>  You knew but little very little<lb/> of him&#44; but had you known his<lb/> deep learning which his meekness<lb/> but too much concealed&#8212;his<lb/> true piety&#44; his manly upright<lb/> hearing and sterling worth&#8212;had<lb/> you ever seen him in the<lb/> domestic circle and observed<lb/> how all his children without<lb/> exception <sic>idolised</sic> him&#8212;and<lb/> how among the married ones<lb/> the tie was equally strong&#44; you<lb/> could somewhat <sic>realise</sic> the bitter<lb/> grief of his children&#44; and the<lb/> force of the blow which prostrated me<lb/> But through the mercy of the<lb/> Righteous Judge&#44; I was not life<lb/> without much consolation form<lb/> above&#59; his reputation&#44; and the<lb/> numerous warm sympathizing</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>friends his widow &#38; children<lb/> found&#8212;the deep seated regret<lb/> which even now pervades his late<lb/> congregation who have mostly<lb/> grown up under him&#8212;and who<lb/> without exception respected and<lb/> loved him as a father&#44; would not<lb/> be without consoling influence.<lb/>  Never was Minister so universally<lb/> loved&#44; and respected by the<lb/> sister congregations in <placeName>England</placeName>.<lb/>  But Gods will be done <add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I presume you are aware<lb/> my brother <persName>Samuel</persName> has&#44; in accordance<lb/> with my late fathers design &#38; wish<lb/> been appointed as assistant Hazan<lb/> for two years&#44; and it is the unanimous<lb/> desire of the <add>Hebrew</add> that he qualify himself<lb/> as a lecturer.  He has matriculated<lb/> &#40;after 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> honors at Jews College&#41; at the<lb/> London University for his degree of B. A.<lb/> More of this some other time.  I must<lb/> now close.</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName></p>
		</body>
